All governors of provinces had fixed salaries from the treasury3 and cruelty and extortion, though by no means things οἱ the past, enjoyed far less impunity than such as collusive accusem, or judges interested in connivance, had often secured for the culprit in former times. From this cause, probably also from the more equitable assessment of tribute through a systematic census, the provinces are admitted to have been gainers by the fall of the Republic, and there is evidence that those placed under the emperor were more economically governed than the senatorial.

§ 20. Several states and kingdoms not formally reduced to provinces, but left semi-independent under native rulers, helped to strengthen the empire against hostile nations ².

ξ 21. The great military force of the empire was massed along its north-eastern frontier, formed, roughly speaking, by the Rhine, Danube, and Euphrates. The eight legions of Germany and the four of Syria have been already mentioned; the line of the Danube was secured by five in Moesia and Pannonia, supported by two more in Dalmatia3 to these are to be added two in Egypt, one in Africa, and three in Spain, making up the whole standing force of twenty-five legions. Italy had no other garrison than the prae- torian and urban cohorts (whose head quarters were in Rome), and the fleets of Misenum and Ravenna.

ξ 22. The legion, commanded by a legatus of senatorial, often even of praetorian rank, consisted of ten cohorts, each subdivided into three maniples, each of which contained two centuries. All its soldierS‚ though recruited freely from all parts of the empire, were Roman citizens; but a large auxiliary or non-citizen force was always attached to it, supplementing it chiefly with light troops and cavalry: the whole corps being thus made up to a strength of about 10,000 of all arms and descriptions.
